Rating: 2
I made this cake the other day, careful to follow the directions after reading all the reviews. The end result was a soft, moist yellow cake. It wasn't flat, it had volume, but I wouldn't exactly describe it as 'fluffy'. I made two 8-inch cakes, brushed each layer with sugar syrup (boil equal amounts of water and granulated sugar for 2-3 minutes, use once it's cooled off. this prevents thick creamy frostings like buttercream from making the cake soggy.) I used the cream cheese buttercream frosting recipe from the ORANGE LAYER CAKE WITH BUTTERCREAM FROSTING AND BERRIES recipe on epicurious, from Bon Appétit, June 2006, minus the orange flower water. I soaked banana slices in lime juice to keep them from turning brown, and put a layer of them in the buttercream between the two cake layers. On the top and sides I put fresh slices of strawberries and blueberries. The fruit and frosting combo tasted amazing, and the entire cake was decent, but next time I think I'll use a fluffier, lighter tasting cake. I did use softasilk cake flour. While the sugar syrup kept the icing from sogging up the cake, it unfortunately did seep into the cake somewhat, making it a bit less soft on the edges. Also, the icing I used was delicious, but it is a pain to navigate with for more than ten minutes at a time. All around, made a decent, pretty cake. But I probably will not make it again, just because it's not what I needed, not because it's not a good recipe!

Rating: 4
The earlier reviewer who left the "food scientists" comment about bitterness in this cake was wrong: if you have baking soda in a cake but not enough acidic ingredients in the cake to counteract it, you will get a residual bitterness. But you can use buttermilk as this cake does without leaving any bitterness behind; extra acid might add a touch of tangy, sour flavor, but it won't be bitter. In this recipe, the buttermilk reacts with the baking soda contained in the baking powder to provide a leavening effect.

