I've finally mastered cake baking with this recipe! I've had problems in the past with my homemade cakes -- too dense, too grainy, or too greasy. I followed the recipe exactly, even used a thermometer to ensure the butter was room temperature (70 F). (I've been guilty in the past of microwaving my butter to speed the process, but now I'm convinced letting the butter sit is worth the wait.) I especially took note of the advice offered by the cook in Boise -- I actually timed the beating of my butter and butter/sugar/egg mixture. I took the mixer off the stand and beat the dry ingredients (alternating with the buttermilk) in by hand, so as to not overmix. The cake was perfectly even, light, moist, and tasted heavenly. I frosted it with a cream cheese frosting. Very good, but I'll try chocolate next time. My office co-workers are actually now eating it for breakfast as I type this.

Rating: 4
In order to produce a light and fluffy texture, the butter and sugar must be beaten until light and fluffy. Also, once the flour mixture is added, you need to use a light hand - otherwise, you get heavy, dense cake! I am an experienced, self-taught baker and chef, and it took me years to figure these steps out. If you happen to have a stand mixer, there is an easier way. This method is called the "two stage" method, and is described in "The Cake Bible," by Rose Levy Berenbaum (who contributes articles to this site, by the way).

Rating: 4
A very nice texture -- light and moist. I varied the recipe by replacing the buttermilk with pineapple juice, then split the layers (to make four) and put pineapple filling between them. With creamcheese frosting, it was a huge hit.

